the 3-point spectral Pick interpolation problem and
an application to holomorphic correspondences

Vikramjeet Singh Chandel Department of Mathematics, Indian Institute of Science, Bangalore 560012, India vikramjeetc@iisc.ac.in
Abstract.

We provide a necessary condition for the existence of a 333-point holomorphic interpolant F:𝔻⟶Ωn:𝐹⟶𝔻subscriptΩ𝑛F:\mathbb{D}\longrightarrow\Omega_{n}, n≥2𝑛2n\geq 2. Our condition is inequivalent to the necessary conditions hitherto known for this problem. The condition generically involves a single inequality and is reminiscent of the Schwarz lemma. We combine some of the ideas and techniques used in our result on the 𝒪​(𝔻,Ωn)𝒪𝔻subscriptΩ𝑛\mathcal{O}(\mathbb{D},\,\Omega_{n})-interpolation problem to establish a Schwarz lemma — which may be of independent interest — for holomorphic correspondences from 𝔻𝔻\mathbb{D} to a general planar domain Ω⋐ℂdouble-subset-ofΩℂ\Omega\Subset\mathbb{C}.

Key words and phrases:
spectral unit ball, minimal Blaschke product, holomorphic functional calculus, holomorphic correspondences

Primary: 30E05, 32H35, 47A56; Secondary: 32F45

1. Introduction and statement of results

Let 𝔻𝔻\mathbb{D} denote the open unit disc in the complex plane ℂℂ\mathbb{C} centered at 00. Given n∈ℤ+𝑛subscriptℤn\in\mathbb{Z}_{+} the n2superscript𝑛2n^{2}-dimensional spectral unit ball is the set Ωn:={A∈Mn​(ℂ):σ​(A)⊂𝔻}assignsubscriptΩ𝑛conditional-set𝐴subscript𝑀𝑛ℂ𝜎𝐴𝔻\Omega_{n}:=\{A\in M_{n}(\mathbb{C})\,:\,\sigma(A)\subset\mathbb{D}\}, where Mn​(ℂ)subscript𝑀𝑛ℂM_{n}(\mathbb{C}) denotes the set of all n×n𝑛𝑛n\times n complex matrices and σ𝜎\sigma denotes the spectrum of a matrix. The interpolation problem referred to in the title of this article is the following problem:

  • (∗)(*)

    Given M𝑀M distinct points ζ1,…,ζM∈𝔻subscript𝜁1…subscript𝜁𝑀𝔻\zeta_{1},\dots,\zeta_{M}\in\mathbb{D} and matrices W1,…,WM∈Ωnsubscript𝑊1…subscript𝑊𝑀subscriptΩ𝑛W_{1},\dots,W_{M}\in\Omega_{n}, n≥2𝑛2n\geq 2, find conditions on the data {(ζj,Wj):1≤j≤M}conditional-setsubscript𝜁𝑗subscript𝑊𝑗1𝑗𝑀\{(\zeta_{j},\,W_{j}):1\leq j\leq M\} such that there exists a holomorphic map F:𝔻⟶Ωn:𝐹⟶𝔻subscriptΩ𝑛F:\mathbb{D}\longrightarrow\Omega_{n} satisfying F​(ζj)=Wj,j=1,…,Mformulae-sequence𝐹subscript𝜁𝑗subscript𝑊𝑗𝑗1…𝑀F(\zeta_{j})=W_{j},\ j=1,\dots,M.

When such a function F𝐹F exists, we shall say that F𝐹F is an interpolant of the data.

One of the important steps towards understanding the problem (∗)(*) was an operator-theoretic approach due to Bercovici, Foias and Tannenbaum. Using a spectral version of the commutant-lifting theorem, the authors in [4] — under the restriction that supζ∈𝔻ρ​(F​(ζ))<1subscriptsupremum𝜁𝔻𝜌𝐹𝜁1\sup_{\zeta\in\mathbb{D}}\rho(F(\zeta))<1, where ρ𝜌\rho denotes the spectral radius — provided a characterization for the existence of an interpolant. This characterization involves a search for M𝑀M appropriate matrices in G​Ln​(ℂ)𝐺subscript𝐿𝑛ℂGL_{n}(\mathbb{C}).

Another influential idea was introduced by Agler and Young in [1]. They observed that in the case W1,…,WMsubscript𝑊1…subscript𝑊𝑀W_{1},\dots,W_{M} are all non-derogatory, then (∗)(*) is equivalent to an interpolation problem from 𝔻𝔻\mathbb{D} to the n𝑛n-dimensional symmetrized polydisc Gnsubscript𝐺𝑛G_{n}, n≥2𝑛2n\geq 2. This is a bounded domain in ℂnsuperscriptℂ𝑛\mathbb{C}^{n} (see [8] for the definition of Gnsubscript𝐺𝑛G_{n}). Its relevance to (∗)(*) is that, for “generic” matricial data (W1,…,WM)subscript𝑊1…subscript𝑊𝑀(W_{1},\dots,W_{M}), the problem (∗)(*) descends to a region of much lower dimension with many pleasant properties. This idea has further been developed in [2], in the papers [7] and [8] by Costara, and in Ogle’s thesis [14]. A matrix A∈Mn​(ℂ)𝐴subscript𝑀𝑛ℂA\in M_{n}(\mathbb{C}) is said to be non-derogatory if it admits a cyclic vector. It is a fact that A𝐴A being non-derogatory is equivalent to A𝐴A being similar to the companion matrix of its characteristic polynomial (see [11, p. 195], for instance). By way of the Gnsubscript𝐺𝑛G_{n}-interpolation problem, Costara [8] and Ogle [14] arrived independently at a necessary condition for the existence of an interpolant for the problem (∗)(*) when the data (W1,…,WM)subscript𝑊1…subscript𝑊𝑀(W_{1},\dots,W_{M}) are non-derogatory.

Bharali in [5] observed that when n≥3𝑛3n\geq 3, the necessary condition given in [8, 14] is not sufficient. He also established — for the case M=2𝑀2M=2 — a new necessary condition for the existence of an interpolant. Result 1.1 below is this necessary condition. It is reminiscent of the inequality in the classical Schwarz lemma; here ℳ𝔻​(z1,z2)subscriptℳ𝔻subscript𝑧1subscript𝑧2\mathcal{M}_{\mathbb{D}}(z_{1},z_{2}) is the Möbius distance between z1subscript𝑧1z_{1} and z2subscript𝑧2z_{2}, which is defined as:

The above theorem gives a necessary condition for the two-point interpolation problem without any restriction on the matrices, in contrast to the necessary condition in [8, 14]. In the same article, Bharali also shows that for each n≥3𝑛3n\geq 3, there exists a data-set for which (1.1) implies that it cannot admit an interpolant whereas the condition in [8, 14] is inconclusive.

Remark 1.5.

Theorem 1.4, unlike Result 1.3, incorporates information about the Jordan structure of the matricial data. Thus, Theorem 1.4 gives a more restrictive inequality than (1.4) if ν=n𝜈𝑛\nu=n. Moreover, in Section 6 we will present a class of 333-point matricial data in 𝔻×Ωn𝔻subscriptΩ𝑛\mathbb{D}\times\Omega_{n}, n≥4𝑛4n\geq 4, for which the condition (1.4) and that in [8, 14] provide no information while Theorem 1.4 implies that these data do not admit a 𝒪​(𝔻,Ωn)𝒪𝔻subscriptΩ𝑛\mathcal{O}(\mathbb{D},\,\Omega_{n})-interpolant.

The above discussion about the role of the Nokrane–Ransford result [13, Theorem 1.1] establishes how holomorphic correspondences are naturally related to the problem (∗)(*). This is why we also consider holomorphic correspondences in this paper. Indeed, the method that we employ to provide the proof of Theorem 1.4 motivated our investigation into finding a Schwarz lemma for holomorphic correspondences, which are generalizations of algebroid multifunctions. Before we present our result, we need a few definitions:

Definition 1.6.

Given domains Di⊆ℂnsubscript𝐷𝑖superscriptℂ𝑛D_{i}\subseteq\mathbb{C}^{n}, i=1,2𝑖12i=1,2, a holomorphic correspondence from D1subscript𝐷1D_{1} to D2subscript𝐷2D_{2} is an analytic subvariety ΓΓ\Gamma of D1×D2subscript𝐷1subscript𝐷2D_{1}\times D_{2} of dimension n𝑛n such that π1|Γevaluated-atsubscript𝜋1Γ\left.\pi_{1}\right|_{\Gamma} is surjective (where π1subscript𝜋1\pi_{1} denotes the projection onto D1subscript𝐷1D_{1}).

A proper holomorphic correspondence ΓΓ\Gamma from D1subscript𝐷1D_{1} to D2subscript𝐷2D_{2} is a holomorphic correspondence (as defined above) such that Γ¯∩(D1×∂D2)=∅¯Γsubscript𝐷1subscript𝐷2\overline{\Gamma}\cap(D_{1}\times\partial{D_{2}})=\emptyset. We refer the reader to Section 5 for a discussion as to why holomorphic correspondences with the latter property are called proper holomorphic correspondences. A proper holomorphic correspondence ΓΓ\Gamma from D1subscript𝐷1D_{1} to D2subscript𝐷2D_{2} also induces the following set-valued map:

FΓ​(z):={w∈D2:(z,w)∈Γ}​∀z∈D1.assignsubscript𝐹Γ𝑧conditional-set𝑤subscript𝐷2𝑧𝑤Γfor-all𝑧subscript𝐷1F_{\raisebox{-3.0pt}{$\scriptstyle{\!\Gamma}$}}(z):=\{w\in D_{2}\,:\,(z,w)\in\Gamma\}\;\;\forall z\in D_{1}. (1.5)

The Carathéodory pseudo-distance, denoted by CΩsubscript𝐶ΩC_{\Omega}, on a domain ΩΩ\Omega in ℂℂ\mathbb{C} is defined by:

CΩ​(p,q):=sup{ℳ𝔻​(f​(p),f​(q)):f∈𝒪​(Ω,𝔻)}.assignsubscript𝐶Ω𝑝𝑞supremumconditional-setsubscriptℳ𝔻𝑓𝑝𝑓𝑞𝑓𝒪Ω𝔻C_{\Omega}(p,\,q):=\sup\{\mathcal{M}_{\mathbb{D}}(f(p),\,f(q))\,:\,f\in\mathcal{O}(\Omega,\,\mathbb{D})\}. (1.6)

The reader will notice that we have defined CΩsubscript𝐶ΩC_{\Omega} in terms of the Möbius distance rather than the hyperbolic distance on 𝔻𝔻\mathbb{D}. This is done purposely because most conclusions in metric geometry that rely on CΩsubscript𝐶ΩC_{\Omega} are essentially unchanged if ℳ𝔻subscriptℳ𝔻\mathcal{M}_{\mathbb{D}} is replaced by the hyperbolic distance on 𝔻𝔻\mathbb{D} in (1.6), and because the Möbius distance arises naturally in the proof of our next theorem. We now present this theorem:

Theorem 1.7.

Let ΩΩ\Omega be a bounded domain in ℂℂ\mathbb{C} and let ΓΓ\Gamma be a proper holomorphic correspondence from 𝔻𝔻\mathbb{D} to ΩΩ\Omega. Then for every ζ1,ζ2∈𝔻subscript𝜁1subscript𝜁2𝔻\zeta_{1},\zeta_{2}\in\mathbb{D} we have:

ℋCΩ​(FΓ​(ζ1),FΓ​(ζ2))≤ℳ𝔻​(ζ1,ζ2)1/n,superscriptℋsubscript𝐶Ωsubscript𝐹Γsubscript𝜁1subscript𝐹Γsubscript𝜁2subscriptℳ𝔻superscriptsubscript𝜁1subscript𝜁21𝑛\mathcal{H}^{C_{\Omega}}\big{(}F_{\raisebox{-3.0pt}{$\scriptstyle{\!\Gamma}$}}(\zeta_{1}),\,F_{\raisebox{-3.0pt}{$\scriptstyle{\!\Gamma}$}}(\zeta_{2})\big{)}\leq{\mathcal{M}_{\mathbb{D}}\left(\zeta_{1},\,\zeta_{2}\right)}^{{1}/{n}},

where ℋCΩsuperscriptℋsubscript𝐶Ω\mathcal{H}^{C_{\Omega}} denotes the Hausdorff distance induced by CΩsubscript𝐶ΩC_{\Omega}, and n𝑛n is the multiplicity of ΓΓ\Gamma.

Here, the multiplicity n𝑛n is as given by Lemma 5.2 (also see Remark 5.4) below. The inequality above reduces to the distance-decreasing property for the Carathéodory pseudo-distance if ΓΓ\Gamma is merely the graph of a holomorphic map F:𝔻⟶Ω:𝐹⟶𝔻ΩF:\mathbb{D}\longrightarrow\Omega. From this perspective, we can view Theorem 1.7 as a Schwarz lemma for proper holomorphic correspondences. It turns out that algebroid multifunctions are precisely the proper holomorphic correspondences from 𝔻𝔻\mathbb{D} to itself (see Lemma 5.2). Hence, Theorem 1.7 generalizes [13, Theorem 1.1] by Nokrane–Ransford.

The above theorem is the consequence of a more precise inequality, which we present in Section 7 as Theorem 7.1. The proof of the latter theorem is closely related to the proof of Theorem 1.4. The proof of Theorem 1.4 is presented in Section 6, while the proof of Theorem 1.7 is presented in Section 7.

4. Two fundamental lemmas

In this section, we state two fundamental and closely related lemmas. Lemma 4.3 serves as the link between the two main results of this paper. Both lemmas are simple, once we appeal to Vesentini’s theorem. We begin by stating this result.

Result 4.1 (Vesentini, [16]).

Let 𝒜𝒜\mathscr{A} be a complex, unital Banach algebra and let ρ​(x)𝜌𝑥\rho(x) denote the spectral radius of any element x∈𝒜𝑥𝒜x\in\mathscr{A}. Let f∈𝒪​(𝔻,𝒜)𝑓𝒪𝔻𝒜f\in\mathcal{O}(\mathbb{D},\,\mathscr{A}). Then, the function ζ⟼ρ​(f​(ζ))⟼𝜁𝜌𝑓𝜁\zeta\longmapsto\rho(f(\zeta)) is subharmonic on 𝔻𝔻\mathbb{D}.

5. Some notations and results in basic complex geometry

This section is devoted to a couple of results in the geometry and function theory in the holomorphic setting that are relevant to our proof of Theorem 1.7. Our first result pertains to the structure of a holomorphic correspondence ΓΓ\Gamma from 𝔻𝔻\mathbb{D} to ΩΩ\Omega with the properties as in Theorem 1.7. For this, we need the following standard result (see [6, Section 3.1], for instance).

Result 5.1.

Let Ω1⊊XsubscriptΩ1𝑋\Omega_{1}\subsetneq X and Ω2⊊YsubscriptΩ2𝑌\Omega_{2}\subsetneq Y be open subsets in topological spaces X𝑋X and Y𝑌Y respectively, with Ω¯2subscript¯Ω2\overline{\Omega}_{2} being compact. Let A𝐴A be a closed subset in Ω1×Ω2subscriptΩ1subscriptΩ2\Omega_{1}\times\Omega_{2}. Then the restriction to A𝐴A of the projection (x,y)⟼x⟼𝑥𝑦𝑥(x,\,y)\longmapsto x is proper if and only if A¯∩(Ω1×∂Ω2)=∅¯𝐴subscriptΩ1subscriptΩ2\overline{A}\cap(\Omega_{1}\times\partial{\Omega_{2}})=\emptyset.

Owing to the above result, any holomorphic correspondence ΓΓ\Gamma from D1subscript𝐷1D_{1} to D2subscript𝐷2D_{2}, which are domains in ℂnsuperscriptℂ𝑛\mathbb{C}^{n}, such that Γ¯∩(D1×∂D2)=∅¯Γsubscript𝐷1subscript𝐷2\overline{\Gamma}\cap(D_{1}\times\partial{D_{2}})=\emptyset is called a proper holomorphic correspondence. However, since that discussion pertains to a much more general setting, we provide a proof in the set-up that we are interested in.

Remark 5.4.

The positive integer n𝑛n that appears in the above lemma is known as the multiplicity of ΓΓ\Gamma. In general, when we have a proper holomorphic correspondence ΓΓ\Gamma from Ω1subscriptΩ1\Omega_{1} to Ω2subscriptΩ2\Omega_{2} with dim(Γ)=dim(Ω1)dimensionΓdimensionsubscriptΩ1\dim(\Gamma)=\dim(\Omega_{1}), then there exists an analytic variety 𝒜⊂Ω1𝒜subscriptΩ1\mathcal{A}\subset\Omega_{1} with dim𝒜<dim(Γ)dimension𝒜dimensionΓ\dim{\mathcal{A}}<\dim(\Gamma) such that the cardinality of π1−1​{z}∩Γ=ksuperscriptsubscript𝜋11𝑧Γ𝑘\pi_{1}^{-1}\{z\}\cap\Gamma=k for all z∈Ω∖𝒜𝑧Ω𝒜z\in\Omega\setminus\mathcal{A} (see [6, Section 3.7]). We shall now look at an extremal problem associated to the Carathéodory pseudo-distance CΩsubscript𝐶ΩC_{\Omega} on the domain ΩΩ\Omega in ℂℂ\mathbb{C}. Recall the discussion in Section 1 about the Carathéodory pseudo-distance, and the reasons that we prefer using the following definition:

Theorem 1.7 is a corollary of Theorem 7.1. This is almost immediate; we probably just require a few words about the Hausdorff distance induced by CΩsubscript𝐶ΩC_{\Omega}. We refer the reader to [12, p. 279] for the definition of the Hausdorff distance — which is a distance on the set of non-empty closed, bounded subsets of a distance space (X,d)𝑋𝑑(X,\,d).
